In TypeScript, you can use the `never` type to explicitly assert that a value will never be of a certain type or union of types. This is useful when you know that a value will only have a specific type, even though it could theoretically have other types.

Here's an example of how you can use `never` to restrict the type of a variable:
```typescript
function doSomething(value: never NeverType) {
  // value will only ever have type'someType'
  const specificType:'someType' = value;
}
```
In this example, the `doSomething` function accepts a `value` parameter with a type assigned to it as `never NeverType`. This means that the value will never be of the `NeverType` type. You can then assign the `value` to a more specific type, such as `specificType:'someType'`.

Keep in mind that using `never` can be seen as an assertion that the value will never be of a certain type, so be cautious when using it. If you're unsure about the types that a variable might have, you may want to consider using a more generic type or type constraints to narrow down the possible types.

